1
00:00:02,292 --> 00:00:05,667
( MUSIC PLAYING )

2
00:00:56,000 --> 00:00:59,416
( BURPS )
( GIGGLES )

3
00:00:59,417 --> 00:01:02,333
Excuse me, Thomas!

4
00:01:03,333 --> 00:01:05,333
( SIGHS )

5
00:01:06,750 --> 00:01:08,333
Well, what should I
do now, Thomas?

6
00:01:11,833 --> 00:01:15,250
Go on, tell me!

7
00:01:41,958 --> 00:01:45,207
Thomas?

8
00:01:45,208 --> 00:01:47,625
Why have you stopped
talking to me?

9
00:01:49,167 --> 00:01:50,375
Thomas?

10
00:01:52,583 --> 00:01:54,667
Thomas Dawnston, are you there?

11
00:02:13,292 --> 00:02:17,000
All right, who's the wise guy?

12
00:02:18,250 --> 00:02:21,375
( THUNDER )

13
00:02:23,292 --> 00:02:25,052
Well, if you're not Thomas,
then who are you?

14
00:02:28,292 --> 00:02:30,917
Identify yourself please.

15
00:02:39,708 --> 00:02:43,000
Ahhh...

16
00:02:45,542 --> 00:02:48,791
Guuu...

17
00:02:48,792 --> 00:02:51,042
Staaa...

18
00:02:56,292 --> 00:02:59,458
Laaa...

19
00:03:00,500 --> 00:03:02,292
Oooh.

20
00:03:03,750 --> 00:03:06,292
Agusta Lao?

21
00:03:07,833 --> 00:03:11,291
( THUNDER )

22
00:03:11,292 --> 00:03:13,208
( WIND BLOWING )

23
00:03:38,667 --> 00:03:41,832
No!

24
00:03:41,833 --> 00:03:43,666
( GLASSES BREAKING )

25
00:03:43,667 --> 00:03:45,667
Why are you doing this?

26
00:03:48,667 --> 00:03:49,667
Noo!

27
00:03:53,375 --> 00:03:56,625
Nooo!

28
00:04:57,375 --> 00:05:00,624
Uh-oh!

29
00:05:00,625 --> 00:05:02,457
Oh, great!

30
00:05:02,458 --> 00:05:04,167
Now I'm gonna miss the movie.

31
00:05:06,292 --> 00:05:08,874
Well, maybe it's just as well.

32
00:05:08,875 --> 00:05:11,749
I'm not so sure your mother
would approve of you

33
00:05:11,750 --> 00:05:13,910
watching all that scary stuff
just before going to bed.

34
00:05:14,292 --> 00:05:17,749
It wasn't that scary.

35
00:05:17,750 --> 00:05:19,291
Oh no?

36
00:05:19,292 --> 00:05:21,252
Well you know, actually
that toy monkey reminds me

37
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:25,832
of a story I once wrote
for television.

38
00:05:25,833 --> 00:05:29,332
Let's see, what was it?

39
00:05:29,333 --> 00:05:31,832
Of course, Merlin!

40
00:05:31,833 --> 00:05:34,249
Merlin?

41
00:05:34,250 --> 00:05:35,707
Merlin The Sorcerer.

42
00:05:35,708 --> 00:05:37,374
Only it didn't take place
in the time of King Arthur.

43
00:05:37,375 --> 00:05:40,292
You see Merlin used his powers
to come to our time,

44
00:05:40,708 --> 00:05:44,667
to set up a shop of mystical
wonders for all to see.

45
00:05:47,292 --> 00:05:50,666
Mystical wonders?

46
00:05:50,667 --> 00:05:53,499
What are you talking
about, Grandpa?

47
00:05:53,500 --> 00:05:55,458
I'm talking about
magical things,

48
00:05:57,333 --> 00:06:00,582
crystal balls,

49
00:06:00,583 --> 00:06:03,166
enchanted stones,

50
00:06:03,167 --> 00:06:05,448
wondrous objects that Merlin
has collected over the years.

51
00:06:07,208 --> 00:06:10,624
What does he do with them?

52
00:06:10,625 --> 00:06:12,792
Why...

53
00:06:14,833 --> 00:06:18,541
he sells them,
or even gives them away.

54
00:06:18,542 --> 00:06:22,333
And then,
something magical happens

55
00:06:23,500 --> 00:06:27,292
that changes
a person's life forever.

56
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:31,332
Like what?

57
00:06:31,333 --> 00:06:33,332
Young man,

58
00:06:33,333 --> 00:06:35,173
are you actually asking me
to tell you a story?

59
00:06:36,417 --> 00:06:39,332
Yeah sure,
until the lights come back on.

60
00:06:39,333 --> 00:06:42,582
Oh really?
Well here.

61
00:06:42,583 --> 00:06:45,124
You hold on to that,
and I'll tell you the story.

62
00:06:45,125 --> 00:06:48,874
Only, let me see,
it's been a few years

63
00:06:48,875 --> 00:06:51,916
so you'll have to forgive me

64
00:06:51,917 --> 00:06:53,541
if I can't remember it
exactly as it was written.

65
00:06:53,542 --> 00:06:56,832
Go for it!

66
00:06:56,833 --> 00:06:57,916
Go for it, eh?
All right.

67
00:06:57,917 --> 00:07:00,332
Well, the story begins

68
00:07:00,333 --> 00:07:02,792
in a small town
in Northern California.

69
00:07:03,292 --> 00:07:06,792
On a starry night...

70
00:07:13,167 --> 00:07:16,417
( ALARM RINGING )

71
00:09:10,500 --> 00:09:14,332
Nicholas, did you see
where Mommy put her keys?

72
00:09:14,333 --> 00:09:17,166
Susan!

73
00:09:17,167 --> 00:09:18,332
Hi!

74
00:09:18,333 --> 00:09:19,666
How are you?
I haven't seen you in ages!

75
00:09:19,667 --> 00:09:21,332
Great!
How are you?

76
00:09:21,333 --> 00:09:22,582
I'm okay.

77
00:09:22,583 --> 00:09:23,583
So how are you
and Mr. Excitement?

78
00:09:23,584 --> 00:09:25,332
Oh, we're fine.

79
00:09:25,333 --> 00:09:26,333
He's around here somewhere.

80
00:09:26,334 --> 00:09:27,541
How about you and Mel?

81
00:09:27,542 --> 00:09:28,707
Not bad, no complaints.

82
00:09:28,708 --> 00:09:31,082
Wow, I can't get over
how good you look!

83
00:09:31,083 --> 00:09:33,458
You must have lost...

84
00:09:48,292 --> 00:09:51,667
( DOOR CREAKS )

85
00:10:32,333 --> 00:10:35,708
( OWL HOOTS )

86
00:10:46,750 --> 00:10:49,999
Well!

87
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:51,640
Look who we have here,
our first customer!

88
00:10:51,792 --> 00:10:55,291
Merl!
We have a visitor!

89
00:10:55,292 --> 00:10:58,499
Have you found
something you like?

90
00:10:58,500 --> 00:11:01,332
Cat got your tongue?

91
00:11:01,333 --> 00:11:02,667
Hmm?

92
00:11:36,667 --> 00:11:40,416
I got the results
from my doctor yesterday.

93
00:11:40,417 --> 00:11:42,541
Oh I'm sorry.

94
00:11:42,542 --> 00:11:45,499
The thing is, we haven't been
getting along that wellfor some
time now and well, I know he resents me

95
00:11:45,500 --> 00:11:48,666
for not being able to
get pregnant on our own.

96
00:11:48,667 --> 00:11:51,832
Just getting him to go
to the fertility expert

97
00:11:51,833 --> 00:11:53,999
was a giant blow to his ego
and now after everything,

98
00:11:54,000 --> 00:11:57,249
when he finds out
there's no hope at all,

99
00:11:57,250 --> 00:11:59,291
he's just gonna...

100
00:11:59,292 --> 00:12:00,499
SUSAN: You mean,
you haven't told him?

101
00:12:00,500 --> 00:12:03,166
I haven't had the nerve.

102
00:12:03,167 --> 00:12:04,332
I just...

103
00:12:04,333 --> 00:12:05,373
I really wanted this baby.

104
00:12:07,042 --> 00:12:09,666
SUSAN:
You could always adopt.

105
00:12:09,667 --> 00:12:11,082
Jonathan would never
raise someone else's baby,

106
00:12:11,083 --> 00:12:13,166
you know him.

107
00:12:13,167 --> 00:12:16,416
SUSAN: But having a child
is so important to you.
Wouldn't he...

108
00:12:16,417 --> 00:12:18,000
No.

109
00:12:24,458 --> 00:12:27,875
Hello, Susan.

110
00:12:28,958 --> 00:12:30,749
MERLIN: Well, Mother,
what do we have here?

111
00:12:30,750 --> 00:12:33,999
Doesn't he remind you
of someone?

112
00:12:34,000 --> 00:12:36,499
Arthur, you old hoot.
Who else?

113
00:12:36,500 --> 00:12:39,082
Oh, yes!
Of course!

114
00:12:39,083 --> 00:12:42,041
How foolish of me.

115
00:12:42,042 --> 00:12:43,374
( LAUGHS )

116
00:12:43,375 --> 00:12:45,999
But I bet your name
isn't Arthur.

117
00:12:46,000 --> 00:12:49,292
Don't tell me.
Don't tell me.

118
00:12:54,833 --> 00:12:58,291
And it's Nicholas.

119
00:12:58,292 --> 00:13:01,291
Isn't it?

120
00:13:01,292 --> 00:13:02,957
Well Nicholas,
do you believe in magic?

121
00:13:02,958 --> 00:13:05,332
You do?
Oh, I knew it!

122
00:13:05,333 --> 00:13:08,833
Oh, you see, Mother,
we're not too late.

123
00:13:10,208 --> 00:13:13,499
There's still hope.

124
00:13:13,500 --> 00:13:15,416
( GROWLING )

125
00:13:15,417 --> 00:13:18,707
That's enough out of you,
Gwen, behave yourself! Oh!
( GLASS BREAKS )

126
00:13:18,708 --> 00:13:20,332
That's your fault!

127
00:13:20,333 --> 00:13:21,292
Yes, yes.

128
00:13:21,292 --> 00:13:22,292
You didn't pick her up
last night, did you?

129
00:13:22,293 --> 00:13:23,374
You know how she gets!

130
00:13:23,375 --> 00:13:25,291
I know.
It won't happen again.

131
00:13:25,292 --> 00:13:27,999
Now, what could we do
for our young friend?

132
00:13:28,000 --> 00:13:31,833
Come here Nicholas,
how would you like to see

133
00:13:32,292 --> 00:13:35,749
one of my favorite tricks?

134
00:13:35,750 --> 00:13:37,916
You would?

135
00:13:37,917 --> 00:13:39,291
It's one of my favorite tricks!

136
00:13:39,292 --> 00:13:42,083
Nothing up my sleeve,
oh rrrrraaaa...

137
00:13:43,167 --> 00:13:46,332
Hahaha!

138
00:13:46,333 --> 00:13:49,916
Oh, now watch closely!

139
00:13:49,917 --> 00:13:53,000
( LAUGHS )
Oh!

140
00:13:55,500 --> 00:13:57,000
Oh.

141
00:14:00,292 --> 00:14:03,291
There take good care of it.

142
00:14:03,292 --> 00:14:04,832
JONATHAN:
That's very amusing.

143
00:14:04,833 --> 00:14:06,291
Is that the extent
of your power as magician?

144
00:14:06,292 --> 00:14:08,874
Oh, I'm sorry, Merlin.

145
00:14:08,875 --> 00:14:11,666
May we help you?

146
00:14:11,667 --> 00:14:13,999
Yeah, allow me
to introduce myself.

147
00:14:14,000 --> 00:14:17,000
My name is Jonathan Cooper III.

148
00:14:23,167 --> 00:14:26,833
Interesting shop.
Heavy atmosphere.

149
00:14:28,333 --> 00:14:29,613
No sign of
contemporary influence

150
00:14:32,208 --> 00:14:33,874
in design or structure.

151
00:14:33,875 --> 00:14:37,041
Shop is at best,

152
00:14:37,042 --> 00:14:38,625
overly theatrical.

153
00:14:39,958 --> 00:14:41,758
Uh, excuse me,
was there something you wanted?

154
00:14:43,292 --> 00:14:46,791
What I want is a story.

155
00:14:46,792 --> 00:14:49,541
Oh.

156
00:14:49,542 --> 00:14:51,041
I am a respected columnist
in this town,

157
00:14:51,042 --> 00:14:53,999
and I'm here to decide
whether or not your shop

158
00:14:54,000 --> 00:14:56,749
is worthy of my readers'
time and money.

159
00:14:56,750 --> 00:15:00,457
Worthy?
What do you mean, worthy?

160
00:15:00,458 --> 00:15:03,291
Nicholas, what are you
doing in here?

161
00:15:03,292 --> 00:15:04,791
Come on, you know better
than to wander off like
that.

162
00:15:04,792 --> 00:15:07,624
( CHICKEN FLYING )

163
00:15:07,625 --> 00:15:09,166
Oh!
( LAUGHING )

164
00:15:09,167 --> 00:15:12,332
Where'd that chicken come from?

165
00:15:12,333 --> 00:15:14,291
What chicken?

166
00:15:14,292 --> 00:15:16,124
SUSAN: Nicholas,
come on, let's go.

167
00:15:16,125 --> 00:15:19,582
Oh Nicholas!
Come back soon.

168
00:15:19,583 --> 00:15:22,291
Okay?

169
00:15:22,292 --> 00:15:23,332
Uh-huh.

170
00:15:23,333 --> 00:15:24,333
Take care, Susan.

171
00:15:24,334 --> 00:15:26,166
Remember what I said.
Call me.

172
00:15:26,167 --> 00:15:28,332
I will.

173
00:15:28,333 --> 00:15:29,916
ZURELLA:
Goodbye, my dear!

174
00:15:29,917 --> 00:15:32,000
SUSAN: Nicholas,
what were you doing...

175
00:15:33,292 --> 00:15:35,083
ZURELLA:
Isn't he precious?

176
00:15:36,667 --> 00:15:38,624
JONATHAN: Merchandise consists
of knick knacks, statues,

177
00:15:38,625 --> 00:15:42,291
various psychic paraphernalia

178
00:15:42,292 --> 00:15:43,624
such as crystal balls,
et cetera...

179
00:15:43,625 --> 00:15:46,708
( SNAKE HISSING )

180
00:15:47,708 --> 00:15:49,068
So, tell me,
what's all this about?

181
00:15:52,292 --> 00:15:55,624
Why are you here?

182
00:15:55,625 --> 00:15:58,292
Why has Merlin,
and his wife, I presume...

183
00:16:00,208 --> 00:16:03,332
Zurella.

184
00:16:03,333 --> 00:16:05,166
Zurella, come
to the 20th century?

185
00:16:05,167 --> 00:16:08,666
I don't like your attitude,
young man.

186
00:16:08,667 --> 00:16:10,332
What business is it of yours...
Dear, dear. Mr. Cooper,

187
00:16:10,333 --> 00:16:14,042
I'm here to awaken the world.

188
00:16:14,375 --> 00:16:18,291
JONATHAN: Awaken the world?
From what?

189
00:16:18,292 --> 00:16:21,292
To bring magic back
into the lives of those

190
00:16:21,542 --> 00:16:25,291
who have let
science and technology

191
00:16:25,292 --> 00:16:27,833
cloud their perceptions.

192
00:16:28,167 --> 00:16:32,292
Perceptions of the powers
which truly govern the universe

193
00:16:35,500 --> 00:16:39,333
to believe in the unbelievable.

194
00:16:48,292 --> 00:16:51,791
Oh, there was a time

195
00:16:51,792 --> 00:16:52,832
when wizards commanded
the respect of kings

196
00:16:52,833 --> 00:16:56,457
and all shared
an undisputed belief

197
00:16:56,458 --> 00:17:00,417
in the mystical powers
which guided their lives.

198
00:17:07,083 --> 00:17:11,042
The objects which you see
before you, Mr. Cooper,

199
00:17:11,875 --> 00:17:15,499
are those magical, mystical,

200
00:17:15,500 --> 00:17:19,292
wonders which I have
collected over the years.

201
00:17:22,125 --> 00:17:25,791
And with them,
I shall allow people

202
00:17:25,792 --> 00:17:29,583
to experience
that belief in magic again.

203
00:17:33,667 --> 00:17:37,999
JONATHAN: You really believe
you are Merlin, don't you?

204
00:17:38,000 --> 00:17:40,916
( LAUGHS ) Storeowner's
an eccentric old man

205
00:17:40,917 --> 00:17:44,500
who suffers from delusions
of being a wizard.

206
00:17:45,333 --> 00:17:48,250
MERLIN: I am, Mr. Cooper,
who I say I am.

207
00:17:49,417 --> 00:17:53,499
JONATHAN: Sure you are, pal.
And I'm Lancelot.

208
00:17:53,500 --> 00:17:56,457
Why, you insufferable rumpus.

209
00:17:56,458 --> 00:17:59,416
MERLIN: Mr. Cooper,
I can assure you,

210
00:17:59,417 --> 00:18:03,291
my intentions are
entirely honorable.

211
00:18:03,292 --> 00:18:06,332
This is so beautiful.

212
00:18:06,333 --> 00:18:08,624
I've never seen
anything like it.

213
00:18:08,625 --> 00:18:11,167
It's a laurel,
a very special stone.

214
00:18:12,500 --> 00:18:15,999
A wishing stone.

215
00:18:16,000 --> 00:18:17,999
JONATHAN:
Come on.

216
00:18:18,000 --> 00:18:19,332
For Pete's sake, Madeleine,
don't encourage them.

217
00:18:19,333 --> 00:18:21,624
It's nothing more than a rock.

218
00:18:21,625 --> 00:18:25,042
Make a wish, dear.

219
00:18:27,250 --> 00:18:30,707
Madeleine, it's people like you

220
00:18:30,708 --> 00:18:32,708
that allow this kind of
exploitation to go on.

221
00:18:50,083 --> 00:18:53,417
A most endearing wish.

222
00:19:05,375 --> 00:19:09,166
All right, I've seen enough.

223
00:19:09,167 --> 00:19:11,291
I could be a sport about this.

224
00:19:11,292 --> 00:19:13,166
If you're really Merlin,
prove it.

225
00:19:13,167 --> 00:19:14,999
Show me something.

226
00:19:15,000 --> 00:19:16,332
As they say, knock my socks off.

227
00:19:16,333 --> 00:19:18,333
Ha-ha-ha!
We don't give demonstrations.

228
00:19:19,333 --> 00:19:22,666
Sure you don't.

229
00:19:22,667 --> 00:19:24,416
Listen to me, OB1.

230
00:19:24,417 --> 00:19:26,582
Either you give me something
to write home about,

231
00:19:26,583 --> 00:19:28,832
or your quaint little shop
is history.

232
00:19:28,833 --> 00:19:31,457
Jonathan, let's just go.

233
00:19:31,458 --> 00:19:33,999
Did you hear me, old man?

234
00:19:34,000 --> 00:19:35,291
Do you know who I am?

235
00:19:35,292 --> 00:19:37,249
I am the Supreme Being.

236
00:19:37,250 --> 00:19:40,416
I chew places like this up
and spit them into the toilet.

237
00:19:40,417 --> 00:19:44,291
So I'm gonna give you
one last chance.

238
00:19:44,292 --> 00:19:46,582
You prove to me that you're
Merlin the Great Sorcerer,

239
00:19:46,583 --> 00:19:49,457
or get off the pot.

240
00:19:49,458 --> 00:19:51,332
For God's sake, Jonathan,
just drop it.

241
00:19:51,333 --> 00:19:53,333
Leave these kind people alone.

242
00:19:54,583 --> 00:19:56,063
Dear, why don't you
give him the book?

243
00:20:01,417 --> 00:20:04,707
The book?

244
00:20:04,708 --> 00:20:05,908
Yes, dear, the book.
Your book.

245
00:20:07,375 --> 00:20:10,749
( WHISPERS )

246
00:20:10,750 --> 00:20:13,332
What's going on?

247
00:20:13,333 --> 00:20:16,000
Oh, Mr. Cooper,
I may have something for you

248
00:20:17,292 --> 00:20:21,124
that will provide the proof
you seek.

249
00:20:21,125 --> 00:20:23,958
JONATHAN:
Oh, yeah?

250
00:20:28,500 --> 00:20:32,041
Looks like an old book.

251
00:20:32,042 --> 00:20:33,958
MERLIN:
Oh, that it is, Mr.
Cooper.

252
00:20:34,250 --> 00:20:37,624
It's a book of magic,

253
00:20:37,625 --> 00:20:40,750
my own compilation
of spells and incantations.

254
00:20:42,125 --> 00:20:45,416
More talk of magic?

255
00:20:45,417 --> 00:20:47,874
I told you, the only kind of
magic I believe in

256
00:20:47,875 --> 00:20:50,332
is the magic I have
in these fingers

257
00:20:50,333 --> 00:20:52,332
to make this place...
( SNAPS FINGERS ) ...disappear.

258
00:20:52,333 --> 00:20:55,707
Mr. Cooper, if you would
just take this book home

259
00:20:55,708 --> 00:20:58,832
and read through it,
I assure you,

260
00:20:58,833 --> 00:21:01,207
you will be thoroughly
satisfied.

261
00:21:01,208 --> 00:21:04,667
MERLIN: I'm sure you will find
that it makes good reading.

262
00:21:07,292 --> 00:21:09,667
